You will also recieve a free 4x6 printed copy with the option of a single image or collage (which is perfect to use as a comp card). In this episode of The Simpsons we follow Homer and the reunion of his Mother Mona. After learning that Mr. Burns wants his employees to clean litter from a highway maintained by his company on a Saturday, Homer fakes his own death using a dummy to avoid it. When Marge discovers his scheme the next day, she makes Homer go to the Springfield Hall of Records to explain he is not dead. Afterwards he sees in the record that his mother is still alive. unconvinced, he goes to his mother's grave and discovers that it is actually someones elses. Nearby, homer sees his own grave and falls into it. Homer is approached by a woman who chastises him for falling into her son's grave. Homer recognizes her as his mother Mona, and both embrace each other. He takes her home to meet the family. She also bonds with Lisa, being on the same intellectual level and of the same socially-conscious personality. However, a police car drives by and Mona runs inside the house, making Lisa a little suspicious. The family confronts Mona, who reveals the truth about her past. In 1969, Mona joined a group of hippies to protest a germ warfare laboratory owned by Mr. Burns, which was preparing to poison everyone in Springfield. The group detonated an "antibiotic bomb" inside the lab, killing all the germs. Mr. Burns was trampled by the crew while attempting to stop them. When Mona went back to help Burns, she was recognized as one of the perpetrators, forcing her to leave Homer and go into hiding. Homer then wonders why Mona never contacted him. Mona, insisting that she did send packages, they head to the post office to claim the undelivered packages At the post office, Mr. Burns  recognizes her and calls the FBI. the FBI and Mr. Burns tracks her down back to the Simpsons house and Homer helps Mona escape. Mona realizes that now she must go into hiding leaving Homer  once more. This time, Homer gets to say goodbye to his mother, but it's clear that the pain of her absence will remain. Homer sadly tells his mother to not forget him, and she replies that he will always be a part of her. With Mona driving away, Homer waves into the distance, Homer sits alone on his car and watches the stars into the night as the credits roll.

Happy holidays. ❤️ Three weeks ago, when the vet told me we should probably stop trying to cast Backspace's foot, I felt very resigned. Despite exercises and 4 different casts, his leg continued to stick out behind him when he walked. It was straighter and more flexible, but he just couldn't get into the habit of putting it in front of him. I've worked 10 hour days every day since November and I felt lousy about the fact that I couldn't devote more time to physical therapy now that the cast had failed. Thinking about his leg occupied so much space in my mind because even if the vets said it was time to let it go, I couldn't. I figured that since he's such an easy going kitten and if he was going to lose the leg anyway, perhaps there was no harm in trying a homemade splint. I knew I wanted to keep the toes exposed and to add a curve to his hock. I thought if the splint was very minimal, he'd be more inclined to try to use it so I bought a set of finger splints and cut them to size.  The first prototype I made had a part sticking out the back that made it uncomfortable for him to lift up his leg behind him like he normally did when he walked so he stopped doing that almost immediately. Within days, he started to walk with that foot pointing forward. It's been almost two weeks and his leg has improved drastically. And while Backspace still limps a little and he doesn't always use that leg when he runs, it's clear that it isn't getting in the way like it used to. So the leg may not be perfect, but it's functional and I think it'll just keep getting better with time. I showed our vet a video 3 days after this first splint and she was delighted and fully on board with continuing. She said that she really enjoys seeing how creative rescues can be when working around their limited resources. We learn to make do with what we have and in this case, it meant that after trying a traditional strategy, we went completely homemade and it worked despite our expectations. Themes and metaphors symbolic in children’s play. A child therapist provides clinical examples of what their play may look like in sandtray or play therapy.  1) A closed-off/fenced-in world may symbolize the child’s need for safety and protection, help containing big feelings, or a need to compartmentalize their life. 2) An aggressive world may express the child’s anger with an unclear reason, a lack of control in their life, helplessness, or indirect anger at the therapist.  3) An empty world may show the child’s felt sense of rejection or disapproval, unhappy or empty feelings, or a desire to escape or disappear.  4) A chaotic world may symbolize the child’s inner confusion, low self-regulation, or reflecting a chaotic and disorganized living environment.  5) An unpeopled workd may represent the child’s wish to escape or hide, hostility toward others, or a familiar ity with being alone.  6) A rigid world may express the child’s need for predictability and order or a fear if disapproval or rejection.  Please note: symbolism has a general and individual meaning and it’s important to not jump to conclusions nor pathologize your child’s play.  #playtherapy #sandtraytherapy #parents #teachers #childrensmentalhealth #childhoodtrauma #cyclebreaker

Recipe ⬇️ Chà Bông | Ruốc ~ Pork Meat Floss Sprinkle onto warm rice, sticky rice, congee, or baguette to enjoy! This is my second attempt at making this for my kids. I’m still working on achieving a better result but they are happy with it so I’m sharing how I make it Ingredients: 3-4 lbs Pork Tenderloins or Loins 6 Tbsp Fish Sauce 2 Tbsp Sugar 1 Tsp Salt 1/2 Tsp MSG or substitute with Mushroom Seasoning 2 Tsp White Ground Pepper Prep: In a bowl, mix together fish sauce, salt, sugar and MSG then set aside Pork - Trim any fat or white tissue from the meat & discard Cut pork into 2-3 inch cubes, rinse and pat dry Step 1: Add pork and seasoning to a medium size pot Stir, bring to a simmer, cover with lid, turn heat to low Every few mins, remove lid, flip or stir the meat  Continue with this step for at least 20 minutes After 20 mins, remove lid, turn heat up to medium and let it continue simmering until the liquid has reduced and evaporated Turn off heat Step 2: Add 2-3 pieces of pork to a mortar & pestle or use a meat tenderizer to lightly smash You can also shred by hand just to separate it up a bit Place the pork onto a bamboo tray, rub the meat against the tray to shred  Step 3: Add the shredded pork into a large pan Turn heat to high just to heat the pan up then turn it down low Add white ground pepper, stir well Continuing stirring until the meat turns a light golden color and the texture is fluffy and dry to the touch Note: Do not let the pork sit in the pan without stirring, doing so could cause it to get too dry and crispy To store: Add to a clean mason jar then place into a fridge or freezer Should be good for a couple months as long as you use a clean utensil each time . . . . . #recipe #ngonqua #chabong #ruoc #porkfloss #homemade #homecooked #delicious #food #foodie #foodporn  #asianfood #asiancuisine #fyp #learnontiktok #vietnam #confortfood #vietnamesefood #vietfood #eeeeeats  #jphamskitchen

Newly released satellite images reveal how cities and towns in Gaza have been destroyed by almost three weeks of Israeli bombardments on the besieged enclave. Apartment buildings are crumpled and entire neighbourhoods lie in ruins, in pictures taken before and after Israeli airstrikes and provided by Maxar Technologies and Planet Labs. In Beit Hanoun, which lies close to the northern border with Israel, four- and five-storey buildings are in various states of collapse. Huge chunks are missing from some, others are broken in half and two large complexes lie in piles of rubble. The city lies close to one of the main crossings through which Hamas militants launched their murderous rampage through southern Israel and has been a focus of much of the Israel Defence Forces’ (IDF) firepower. Israel has vowed to wipe out Hamas, which rules Gaza, in retaliation for the 7 October attacks in which they killed more than 1,400 people and took 229 people hostage. Since then, Israel has continuously struck Gaza from the air, imposed a siege and is preparing a ground invasion. The Hamas-run health ministry says more than 7,000 people, many of them civilians, have been killed in the Israeli bombardment. US president Joe Biden has questioned the reliability of the reporting of the death toll, because the health ministry is run by Hamas. Omar Shakir, the Israel and Palestine director at Human Rights Watch, said: “We’ve looked at satellite imagery. We’ve seen the number of buildings, and the numbers that are coming out are in line with what we would expect with what we’re seeing on the ground. video_description: SWA denied our dog and the worst part was this... We’ve been loyal Southwest Airlines customers for over 10 years. We’ve earned their companion pass and A-List status for many of those years (basically SWA’s highest frequent flyer/loyalty status) and we have never had a negative experience as insulting as this.  Yes, I know Southwest has a policy about traveling with pets and that it states on their website that, “The cat or dog must be completely inside the pet carrier and be able to stand up and move around the carrier with ease.” However it seems that the enforcement of this rule is arbitrary and dependent on the agent you happen to come across and their supervisor. We’ve never had issues flying with our 20 lb miniature Schnauzer before this incident and we saw a number of other dogs that were about the same size get past Southwest’s arbitrary screening process. The most insulting part of this entire stressful ordeal was how the SWA supervisor spoke down to me and my daughters. The supervisor’s condescending tone was unnecessary. I stayed as calm as I could during this stressful encounter wanting to discuss the matter, but she refused to answer any of my questions.  Southwest, if you are going to enforce your policies, do so uniformly and with a little more kindness. video_description: ⬇️more info on Koh Lipe for budget travelers: Koh Lipe is one of the best islands to visit if you are young and on a budget!✈️ All prices are in USD! Accommodation: $8 to $12/night per person if you stay in a hostel Food: There are plenty of options for 2$ to $3/meal! You can go even lower than this if you eat a lot of mango sticky rice like me😂 Activities: Swimming and enjoying the beaches is free! However, if you want to go on a snorkeling trip they are usually around $15 to $20 for a day trip. You can also take a short taxi boat ride for $3. Transportation: You can walk everywhere on Koh Lipe as it is a small island. If you want to get a taxi (boat), it’s $3. National park fee (for 5 days): $5.70 (200 baht) Getting there: The easiest way to get to Koh Lipe is by ferry (~$30) from Langkawi, Malaysia. You can also get to Koh Lipe from a lot of places in Thailand although it is quite far from most other Thai islands. Obviously depending on where you are from getting there might be quite expensive which is why I highly recommend making Koh Lipe a part of a longer Southeast Asia trip to fit it in your travel budget! video_description: $1 vs. $25 Canned Sardines 🎣 Tinned Fish Talk 🐟 Beach Cliff Sardines in Soybean Oil 🐟 PYSCIS Sardine Royale 2018 in Olive Oil The point here isn’t to say expensive is always better. I wanted a direct comparison between how sardines are most commonly perceived in the US and an opposite extreme of quality control. For those skeptical how a tin could cost $25 look beyond the can itself. The oil alone is many times more expensive, catch methods, selection, and packing require more labor, and conditions for aging must be maintained. Just as wine can range from $3 to $30, sardines can too. Some affordable tins I like include Trader Joe’s sardines in olive oil for $1.69 or King Oscar brisling sardines in EVOO (AKA Tiny Tots) for $3. Note that taste is subjective and this is just one opinion. At the end of the day buy what YOU like. Browse sardines ranging from $3 to $30 at Rainbow Tomatoes Garden (where I got the PYSCIS tin). This small business not only has the largest selection of tinned fish, they also vet every single one of their 800+ products. #tinnedfish #cannedsardines #sardines

Commentators and online users have called for an Ofcom investigation following a British TV presenter’s interview with a Palestinian politician, which has been described as “racist”. Journalist Julia Hartley-Brewer interviewed Palestinian MP Mustafa Barghouti on TalkTV on Wednesday, in a clip that the broadcaster has since promoted on social media. During the interview, a visibly angry Hartley-Brewer clearly does not like Barghouti’s answers, and says: “We haven’t got time to do the entire history of Benjamin Netanyahu, who is not a popular figure in Israel!” She later adds: “Please don’t say that again, we don’t have time for that, you’ve made that point five times already.” “I don’t know what you have time for,” Barghouti responds. After which, Hartley-Brewer shouts: “For the love of God, let me finish a sentence, man! Maybe you’re not used to women talking, I don’t know, but I’d like to finish the sentence!” Barghouti responds that the interview is “misleading the public”, before briefly answering a follow-up question. Hartley-Brewer concludes the segment by saying: “Sorry to have been a woman speaking to you, but there you are.” The clip has since been viewed millions of times on the social media platform X, with several commentators and social media users condemning the British journalist’s conduct. Barghouti himself took to X following the interview, writing: “The arrogance of a racist and unprofessional journalist.” Meanwhile, the Palestinian ambassador to the UK, Husam Zomlot, described the interview as “the remarkable and sorry state of some journalism in the UK on Palestine”. In response to a request for comment, Ofcom told Middle East Eye that any programme which prompts over 50 complaints “will be included in our weekly audience complaints bulletin, published on a Wednesday”. Barghouti, who is also a physician and medical doctor, is the leader of the Palestinian National Initiative political party. He has been a lawmaker in the Palestinian Authority since 2006.

- Israel's Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has told his supporters that he is working on finding countries ready to "absorb" Palestinians from Gaza. The Israeli newspaper Israel Hayom said Netanyahu made the comments at a meeting of his Likud party on Monday, in which he sought to clarify Israel's plans for after the war had ended. "The world is already discussing the possibilities of voluntary immigration,” he said, adding that a team must be established to “ensure that those who want to leave Gaza to a third country can do so." His words align with statements made by other senior Likud figures who have publicly called on western states to accept refugees from Gaza. Israel's military strategy is seemingly aimed at making Gaza uninhabitable by destroying anything that sustains life, hoping that Palestinians will then “voluntarily” leave. In his testimony, the young man explained that after witnessing soldiers shoot members of his family dead, he managed to gather their bodies in one spot and hide among them for three days in order to survive. In recent days, Euro-Med Human Rights Monitor says it has documented many similar field executions by Israeli forces. The killings are taking place in Gaza City and the northern Gaza Strip - areas placed under a media blackout and cut off by Israeli soldiers from access to hospitals and basic needs. Now as Israeli troops retreat from some locations, surviving residents are revealing details of the shocking crimes committed against them. The 21-year-old was a graduate in communications engineering and was looking for a job before conflict broke out on 7 October. Since then, the healthcare system in the besieged Palestinian territory has broken down under the strain of Israeli military attacks on hospitals, the blockade of fuel and medicine needed to keep medical facilities running and the sheer volume of wounded, as Israel continues its bombing campaign in Gaza. “Feeling a sense of social responsibility, I approached my father, who works as an administrative clerk in the clinic, and expressed my willingness to assist him in his duties,” Musameh told Middle East Eye, explaining how she became a volunteer administrative clerk at the clinic. Al-Shifa Hospital in Gaza City was an early target for Israeli military planners, who said there was a Hamas fortification beneath it.
